  "prompt": "Are there statutes that address money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several statutes that address money laundering in the United States:\n\n1. Federal Level:\n- Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)\n- Money Laundering Control Act of 1986\n- Title 18 U.S. Code Section 1956 (Money Laundering)\n- Title 18 U.S. Code Section 1957 (Monetary Transaction in Criminally Derived Property)\n- USA PATRIOT Act\n\n2. State Level:\n- Many states have their own money laundering statutes that complement federal laws\n- These typically mirror federal provisions but may have specific state-level requirements\n\nKey characteristics of these statutes include:\n- Criminalizing financial transactions involving proceeds from illegal activities\n- Requiring financial institutions to report suspicious transactions\n- Establishing reporting requirements for cash transactions over $10,000\n- Imposing significant criminal penalties and potential asset forfeiture\n- Requiring financial institutions to implement anti-money laundering (AML) compliance programs\n\nPenalties can include:\n- Substantial fines\n- Prison sentences\n- Asset seizure\n- Loss of professional licenses\n\nThese statutes aim to prevent criminals from disguising illegally obtained money as legitimate income.",
